title: Wish You Were Here
name: Wish You Were Here
description:
A Map by Aeonge99

A map of geographically named bands and where they're actually from.

properties.name: Alabama
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99The "sweet home" jokes are too easy. Suffice to say this band was actuallly able to properly name itself.

properties.name: Alaska!
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99San Francisco! Same diff. Fun fact: AllMusic.com lists seven bands named Alaska. Sheesh. These guys are the only ones to incorporate the ever-so-important exclamation point.

properties.name: America
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99Picadilly, London, UKThis UK-bred band couldn\'t name a horse, but they did manage to name their band after their native land (three of the founding members were sons of U.S. Air Force officers stationed in England).

properties.name: Architecture in Helsinki
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99One of the latest geographically misnomered uber-groups (it\'s an octet!), Architecture in Helsinki aren\'t from Helsinki (and we\'re pretty certain they\'re not even architects of any kind).

properties.name: Boards of Canada
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99Despite their name and their geographically-titled album "Trans Canada Highway" experimental chill-out twoism Boards of Canada are actually from the northeast coast of Scotland. Word is they took their name as nod to the soundtracks on films put out by the National Film Board of Canada. Unfortch, it may mean they\'re not as into hockey as one might hope.

properties.name: Boston
properties.description: Posted by StevenleckartBoston, MAAn American rock band, Boston released its debut in 1976. The band was founded by Tom Scholz, who graduated from MIT with a Masters in engineering (!)

properties.name: California Snow Story
properties.description: Posted by Baostar ScotlandCalifornia Snow Story are a Scottish-based band, formed in 2002 by David Skirving. David was a founder member of Glasgow band Camera Obscura.

properties.name: Chicago
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99Nobody repped harder for their towns than the supergroups of the \'60s and \'70s. And Chicago were, by far, the best in the Midwest.

properties.name: I'm From Barcelona
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99Wired\'s (and the Underwire\'s) very own Jake Swearingen said it best when describing this band\'s latest record "Let Me Introduce My Friends": Yet another geographically misnomered megaband — this one’s a 29-strong squad from Sweden. Their sunny alt-pop debut is a poly-Nordic spree of catchy choruses, palm-searing hand claps, and happy-is-the-hipster lyrics."

properties.name: Kansas
properties.description: Posted by StevenleckartWho doesn\'t know "Dust in the Wind"? Founded in Topeka, Kansas in about 1970, this prog-rock quintet released its debut in 1974. Interestingly, an early incarnation of the band was named "Saratoga." Go figure.

properties.name: Nazareth
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99The band\'s Web site says they hail from "a conservative-attitudes Scottish town, not a bustling fashion-conscious metropolis like Glasgow." True. Could that be why they didn\'t name themselves after their hometown? Or is it just because it\'s probably easier to say Nazareth than Dunfermline...?

properties.name: Ohio Players
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99This amazing funk group emerged from the "musical hotbead" of Dayton, Ohio in 1959, according to VH1.com. Another interesting tidbit, they were originally called the Ohio Untouchables. Play on Players.

properties.name: Paris Texas
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99Punk five-piece Paris Texas are from Madison, Wisconsin. But in a completely unrelated (as far as we know) coincidence, there\'s also the 1984 movie "Paris, Texas" that has "The Best Small Town in Texas" as its namesake. No word yet on if actual French Parisians have any say on either matter.

properties.name: Texas Is the Reason
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99We\'re not really sure what the cause is, but Texas is surely to blame. Must be why these guys are in Brooklyn.

properties.name: Tokyo Police Club
properties.description: Posted by Aeonge99Seeking directions to Shibuya? Don\'t ask these four lads. The foursome from Toronto may know how to get you there, but it\'s doubtful. So where did the name come from? Well, guitarist-percussionist Josh Hook told ourbrisbane.com "We did have a couple of times where we’d turn up and people would be like ‘Oh, you’re not Japanese at all.\' There’s not a great explanation to the name. It was a lyric in the song \'Cheer It On\', before we even had a name, and then when we were offered to play Pop Montreal. We needed a name, and we thought about how many people were going to be there and that we needed a name that would stand out in a list. So we chose Tokyo Police Club, and now we’re stuck with it, and that’s great!"
